INSERT Items(ID,Titel,Categorie,Postcode,Locatie,Land,Verkoper,Prijs,Valuta,Conditie,Thumbnail,Beschrijving) VALUES (331311881548,'RGB Modded PAL Nintendo 64 N64 - Model NUS-001(FRA) - Better video signal - NL',3591,'54500','Frankrijk','FR','huiolpm','109.99','EUR','Tweedehands','img331311881548.jpg','<font size="2"><font size="3">It''s a Nintendo 64. The model is NUS-001(FRA) and it has been modded to 
give a RGB signal much better than the original composite signal.<br><br>It''s
 not suffisant to connect a RGB cable to a classic N64 because it can 
only give a composite signal. But this console has been modded and give a
 RGB signal.<br><br></font></font><br><font size="2"><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: bold;">What is the mod you use ? What is the "official mod</span></font></font><b>" ?<br></b><br>The
 mod I use is what we call the "official mod", it has been discovered in
 2011. In fact, it completes the incomplete RGB circuit with components 
that Nintendo planned to use. The RGB output was cancelled by Nintendo 
after the production of the first series consoles has been started. 
That''s why, on these first series consoles in France (and also Japan and
 US), there is a RGB chip and empty locations for components that 
haven''t been put.<br><br>For information, before 2011, the method giving
 the best results consisted on completing these empty locations by 
imitating Super Nintendo RGB circuit and it gave a nice RGB signal.<br><b><font color="#FF0010"><u>But since 2011</u></font></b>,
 a person called and obtained from Nintendo France the list of 
components they planned to use on these empty locations. That''s why this
 mod gives much better result than the old mods.<br><br><b>Which RGB cable can I use ?</b><br><br>You can use normal RGB cable for "<i>PAL Gamecube</i>" or for "<i>PAL Super Nintendo</i>" or for "<i>NTSC Super Nintendo</i>". You don''t need to do anything to the cable.<br>In fact, c<font size="2"><font size="3">ontrary to old obsolete mods, here the 
amplification is integrated in the console (and not in the video cable).</font></font> The amplification is already done by the added components.<br><br><font size="2"><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Can I use my power adapter ? Do I need a power converter ?<br></span><br>You
 can use Nintendo 64 power adapters of your country (Germany, United 
Kingdom, Australia etc.) You don''t need a power converter if you use it.<br><br>I
 can sell you a power cable (look at the accessories list at the end) if
 you live in Europe except UK, Italy, Danemark and Swiss. For these 
countries and non european countries, you must get one in your country.<br></font></font><br><font size="2"><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Can I use it with all TVs ?</span><br><br>If
 you have a TV with CRT (Cathode ray tube), old TVs. In general, there 
is no problem but there are some very very old TVs (before 1995) which 
not support RGB signal, please refer to the manual of the TV. Otherwise,
 if you have more than one scart input on your TV, there is probably 
only one input which support the RGB, you must read the manual of the TV
 or compare display quality in all inputs.<br><br>If you have a recent 
LCD (or Plasma) TV. With some of these TV, the display can be bad (in new LCD TVs, the problem is rarest than the old ones). </font></font><font size="2"><font size="3"><font size="2"><font size="3">The composite signal blurs the video and mix the color that''s why the video signal is bad compared to RGB.</font></font> But </font></font><font size="2"><font size="3"><font size="2"><font size="3">the RGB signal give a display closest to the real display so it shows all the details. </font></font></font></font><font size="2"><font size="3"><font size="2"><font size="3"><font size="2"><font size="3">So,
 sometimes on LCD TV which have high resolution, having the real display
 with all the details can be bad. But now, it''s more rare.<br></font></font></font></font>In general, if the display is bad for N64 RGB it is also bad with all 
the retro consoles with RGB (NES or Super NES or Master System or 
Megadrive with RGB). If you can use one of 
these console with RGB with a good display, there would be no 
problem with N64.<br><br>Generally it''s better to play on retro consoles with a CRT TV.<br><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br>Why is it so expensive ?</span><br><br>The
 NUS-001(FRA) is the only PAL model which can be modded to give a RGB 
signal. This model is very rare (majority of consoles are
 EUR model in France). And it take time to mod it.<br></font></font><br><br><br><br><font size="2"><font size="3">This
 console is sold without RGB cable, 
power cable, controller and jumper pak. For the RGB cable, you can use 
Gamecube or Super Nintendo RGB cable. For the other accessories, you can
 use the one you have 
with your console wherever you are (Germany, UK, Australia, Italy, 
Swiss...).</font></font><br><br><span style="font-weight: bold;">If you want cables, controllers and/or jumper pak, I can add it on your package.</span><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br><br></span>RGB Video cable : 9.89€<br>Official power adapter : 13.99€ (please read the third question of the FAQ)<br>Jumper pak + cover : 9€<br>Expansion Pak (Non official) : 30€ (no more available)<br>Expansion Pak (Official) : 35€<br>Official controller with a stick in perfect condition (different color available) : (no more available)<br>Official controller with a stick in good condition (different color available) : (no more available)<br><font size="2"><font size="3"><font face="Times New Roman">Official gray controller with a new Gamecube style stick : 29.90€</font></font></font><br><br><br><br>The console will be sent from France.<br>Economy Postage : Shipping with tracking but without insurance (about 7-10 working days to the Netherlands).<br>Standard Postage : Shipping with tracking and insurance for the total value (about 2-4 working days to the Netherlands).<br>')
